                           <dim type="left">11</dim>
                         </dimensions>
                         <note>The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line. Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an appropriate aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate script size. This scribe will reduce the font size at the end of lines to avoid having to go onto the next line (e.g., ff. 1r, 4r, 7r, 15r, 18v, etc.). When a line is still too long it is completed above or below the end of the line. In these cases, the scribe places the material above the line (e.g., ff. 3v, 5r, 8v, 10r, 12rv, 14v, 16r, etc.), or below (e.g., ff. 6r, 10v, 14v, 16r, 18r, etc.).</note>
                         <add>Overlooked words of text are written interlinearly (ff. 43r and 146r); and overlooked lines of text are written interlinearly (f. 109v); and in the upper margin with a symbol (┴) marking the location where the text is to be inserted (f. 23v, line 15).</add>
                       </layout>
